==Sanskrit==
===Noun===
'''Gopuram'''
#A '''gopuram''' is a tower abutting the entrance to a Hindu temple, typically consisting of an odd number of tiers. The exact number depends on the degree of funding dedicated to the building.
====Etymology====
The word is most commonly seen in English in architectural usage. It is commonly found in English usage in or in reference to Singapore, a place which many Indian residents.

It is speculated on [http://members.tripod.com/jennifer_polan/submissions/gopuram.html http://members.tripod.com/jennifer_polan/submissions/gopuram.html] that the term originates from Sanskr. "go puram" - the "residence of cows", "go" meaning "cows" and "puram" referring to a city, neighborhood, or residence (as '''pura''' in [[Singapore]]). An alternate speculation is that the "go" element abbreviated '''Govinda''' or '''Gopala''', various Hindu titles for the Deity. These speculations, however, are linguistically and culturally unfounded. The established point of view is that ''ko'' (tam. கோ, as written in ''ko-puram'') is an ancient (but not unusual) Dravidian word for "king", this being common imagery for a god as the ruler of a temple (or state). The use of this "God as the king"-motif in ancient South Indian Hinduism is in a way similar to the same motif in classical Jewish religion. Thus கோ-புரம் is most probably a Dravidian-Indo-Arian nominal compound meaning "the king's fortification", thus declaring the temple to be the castle-fortress of the god-king. -- Kavaiyan, see English Wikipedia, 06:36, 28 February 2006 (UTC)